---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What's the most common Pakenham paving job?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Replacement work on 1990s-2000s era driveways and patios that have failed on Class M reactive clay. Older Pakenham streets (around John Street, Henry Street, Pakenham Hills) have housing stock 25-40 years old where the original concrete driveway is cracked through and the back patio is uneven and weed-infested. Typical job: lift the failed concrete or paving, full base rebuild to current spec (100mm Class 3 compacted, moisture barrier), new driveway in exposed aggregate or segmental block, new patio in bluestone or sandstone. Cost range $15,000-$30,000 for a full driveway-plus-patio replacement. Newer Pakenham streets in Lakeside Boulevard / Heritage Springs-adjacent estates are more like the Cardinia Lakes new-build pattern." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Pakenham has heritage overlays - does that affect paving?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes for a few specific streets - parts of old Pakenham township (around Princes Highway, Henry Street, John Street) have Heritage Overlay (HO) listings that require Council planning approval before changes to the front-of-house presentation. That includes front driveway material choice. For an HO-listed property we usually recommend exposed aggregate (closer to original concrete look) or stencilled-concrete reproducing original brick-pattern paving, rather than modern segmental block. We check the planning scheme at the property address before quoting. Application fees ~$300-$600 + 4-6 week planning approval timeline if needed. Most Pakenham properties aren't HO-listed - the rule only applies to a few specific historic streets." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you do larger acreage paving in Pakenham Upper?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. Pakenham Upper is rural-residential acreage (1-10 acre blocks) above the township. Typical projects are larger format: 100-150m² driveways (often gravel-to-paved upgrades), wraparound veranda paving (60-100m²), large alfresco/pool surround integrations. Materials lean towards natural bluestone, granite or sandstone - owners on acreage typically have 30+ year horizons and budget accordingly. Cost per m² same as our normal pricing but project totals are larger: $25,000-$80,000 range for full hardscape packages. Reactive-clay engineering still applies; sometimes Class H ratings with deeper footings on retaining work." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What's the difference between Pakenham township and Pakenham Lakeside estates?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Pakenham township (the original 1990s housing around the railway station, John Street, Henry Street) is mostly 600-1,000m² blocks with brick-veneer or weatherboard houses 25-40 years old. Paving work is usually replacement-driven - failed driveways and patios needing rebuild. Lakeside (Lakeside Boulevard, Lakeside Square) and Pakenham Heritage Springs are newer 2010s estates with 350-600m² blocks and 4-bed contemporary builds. Paving work there is more like Cardinia Lakes - new build patio + driveway packages, no existing failure, design-from-scratch. Both markets, different briefs, same crew. We work across both routinely." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why do older Pakenham concrete driveways crack so badly?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Three reasons that compound over 25 years on Class M reactive clay: (1) original construction often poured 75mm thick with no mesh and no control joints - by 1990s standards that was acceptable, by 2026 standards it's a guaranteed failure; (2) no moisture barrier means base moisture wicked into slab over decades, weakening the cement matrix from below; (3) seasonal clay heave (20-40mm annually) over 25 winters compounds into wide, random crack patterns. The fix isn't crack-fill (that's cosmetic), it's full demolition and re-pour to current AS 3727 spec - 100mm slab, SL82 mesh, 100mm Class 3 base, moisture barrier, saw-cut control joints. A $11,000 replacement now is cheaper than 5 more years of cosmetic patching." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can you match brick patterns in older Pakenham streets?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Often yes. 1990s/2000s Pakenham used common brick formats (Boral, Austral Bricks, Brikmakers) - common red, common cream, gault grey, gum-blossom red. Most are still in production or have very close current matches. For Heritage Overlay properties we sometimes also do stencilled concrete reproducing the original brick pattern as a Council-acceptable alternative when matched brick isn't sourceable. We bring samples to the site visit so you can compare against existing house brick in your own light before signing." }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Paving & Stonemasonry Pakenham | Driveways, Patios, Replacement | (03) 9003 0108"
  description="Paving and stonemasonry for Pakenham 3810 - exposed-aggregate driveway replacement, bluestone patios, engineered retaining walls. Heritage Overlay aware. Class M reactive-clay base spec."
  canonical="https://officerpavingco.com.au/pakenham/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Pakenham 3810 &middot; Lakeside &middot; Pakenham Upper</span>
      <h1>Paving &amp; stonemasonry in <span class="accent">Pakenham</span>.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        Pakenham splits across three markets - older 1990s/2000s township
        streets needing replacement of failed concrete driveways and patios,
        newer Lakeside-style new-build estates wanting bluestone patios over
        exposed-aggregate driveways, and Pakenham Upper acreage with larger-format
        hardscape projects. We work across all three.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Book a free site visit</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Why Pakenham</span>
      <h2>The Pakenham paving story.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>Replacement work dominates older township streets.</h3>
        <p>
          1990s/2000s Pakenham streets (John Street, Henry Street, Pakenham Hills,
          Princes Highway south side) have housing stock 25-40 years old.
          Original driveways were poured at 75mm thick with no mesh and no
          control joints - acceptable by then-standards, guaranteed failure
          by 2026 standards. The current pattern across these streets:
          <strong>full driveway replacement to current AS 3727 spec</strong>
          (100mm slab, SL82 mesh, 100mm Class 3 base, moisture barrier, saw-cut
          joints) at $9,500-$13,500 for a typical 60m&sup2; double. Crack-fill
          is cosmetic and lasts 18 months; replacement is the actual answer.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Heritage Overlay aware.</h3>
        <p>
          A few historic streets in old Pakenham township (around Princes Highway,
          Henry Street, John Street) have <strong>Heritage Overlay (HO) listings</strong>
          requiring Council planning approval before changes to front-of-house
          presentation. That includes front driveway material choice. For an
          HO-listed property we recommend exposed-aggregate (closer to original
          concrete look) or stencilled-concrete reproducing original brick-pattern
          paving over modern segmental block. Planning application fees
          ~$300-$600 + 4-6 week approval timeline. We check the
          planning scheme at the property address before quoting.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Newer Lakeside / Heritage Springs-adjacent estate work.</h3>
        <p>
          Lakeside Boulevard, Lakeside Square and Pakenham Heritage Springs are
          2010s estates with 350-600m&sup2; blocks and 4-bed contemporary
          builds. Paving work here is the new-build pattern - design-from-scratch
          driveway + alfresco patio + side path packages, typically
          $18,500-$28,500 for the lot. Same Class M reactive-clay
          engineering as Cardinia Lakes.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Pakenham Upper acreage.</h3>
        <p>
          Pakenham Upper (above the township) is rural-residential acreage
          - 1-10 acre blocks. Projects scale up: 100-150m&sup2;
          driveways (often gravel-to-paved upgrades), wraparound veranda paving,
          large alfresco/pool surround integrations. Materials lean towards
          natural bluestone, granite or sandstone with 30+ year horizons. Cost
          per m&sup2; same as standard pricing; project totals run
          $25,000-$80,000 for full hardscape packages. Reactive-clay
          engineering still applies; sometimes Class H ratings with deeper
          footings on retaining work.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Brick-matching for older streets.</h3>
        <p>
          1990s/2000s Pakenham used common brick formats (Boral, Austral Bricks,
          Brikmakers) - common red, common cream, gault grey, gum-blossom
          red. Most are still in production or have close current matches. We
          bring samples to the site visit to compare against existing house brick
          in your own light. For HO properties without sourceable matched brick,
          stencilled concrete reproducing the original pattern is a Council-acceptable
          alternative.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Typical Pakenham jobs.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>60m&sup2; driveway replacement (1990s slab demolition + new exposed agg + crossover): $11,500-$15,500</li>
          <li>Township brick-match patio rebuild (failed 25-year-old paving lifted, base rebuilt, brick-matched re-lay): $7,500-$11,500</li>
          <li>Lakeside new-build driveway + alfresco + side-path package: $18,500-$28,500</li>
          <li>Pakenham Upper acreage wraparound veranda paving 80m&sup2; in bluestone: $17,500-$24,500</li>
          <li>HO planning-approved stencilled-concrete brick-pattern driveway: $9,500-$13,000 + planning fees</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Other service areas.</h2>
      <div class="areas-grid">
        <a class="area-pill" href="/officer/">Officer</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/cardinia-lakes/">Cardinia Lakes</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/beaconsfield/">Beaconsfield</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/heritage-springs/">Heritage Springs</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/cardinia-shire/">All Cardinia Shire</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <div class="cta-block">
        <h2>Free Pakenham paving quote.</h2>
        <p>Replacement of failed concrete + Heritage Overlay-aware design + brick-matched township work.</p>
        <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content:center;">
          <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
          <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Book online</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
